WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.455 align:middle line:90%


00:00:04.455 --> 00:00:06.930 align:middle line:90%
[AUDIO LOGO]

00:00:06.930 --> 00:00:08.910 align:middle line:90%


00:00:08.910 --> 00:00:11.880 align:middle line:90%
[BACKGROUND MUSIC]

00:00:11.880 --> 00:00:18.428 align:middle line:90%


00:00:18.428 --> 00:00:20.220 align:middle line:84%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Welcome
to "Beyond Belief."

00:00:20.220 --> 00:00:23.040 align:middle line:10%
Matt Richtel is with us, a
Pulitzer Prize-winning "New

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:25.710 align:middle line:10%
York Times" reporter,
best-selling author.

00:00:25.710 --> 00:00:27.990 align:middle line:84%
Always great to have you
on the program, Matt.

00:00:27.990 --> 00:00:30.960 align:middle line:84%
>>MATT RICHTEL: George, it is
so nice to see you in person.

00:00:30.960 --> 00:00:32.159 align:middle line:90%
Oftentimes, we're--

00:00:32.159 --> 00:00:34.200 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: On the phone,
doing radio shows.

00:00:34.200 --> 00:00:35.230 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: In the
middle of the night.

00:00:35.230 --> 00:00:35.640 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's right.

00:00:35.640 --> 00:00:36.440 align:middle line:90%
There you go.

00:00:36.440 --> 00:00:39.390 align:middle line:84%
Anyways, tell us about your
new work on creativity.

00:00:39.390 --> 00:00:43.080 align:middle line:10%
>>RICHTEL: Well, it
is related in a way--

00:00:43.080 --> 00:00:47.730 align:middle line:10%
we're at a juncture because
things have exploded.

00:00:47.730 --> 00:00:51.330 align:middle line:10%
Lots of traditional
ways of doing things--

00:00:51.330 --> 00:00:54.420 align:middle line:10%
and you can name
almost any medium--

00:00:54.420 --> 00:00:57.750 align:middle line:10%
have been changed by technology.

00:00:57.750 --> 00:00:59.550 align:middle line:10%
It is an inflection point.

00:00:59.550 --> 00:01:01.500 align:middle line:10%
And it is, in particular,
an inflection point

00:01:01.500 --> 00:01:03.390 align:middle line:10%
for creativity.

00:01:03.390 --> 00:01:05.900 align:middle line:84%
So I stepped back
and spent a couple

00:01:05.900 --> 00:01:08.570 align:middle line:84%
of years looking at the
science of creativity,

00:01:08.570 --> 00:01:13.400 align:middle line:84%
the mystery of creativity, to
try to understand how it works.

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:17.120 align:middle line:84%
And then in addition, why it's
so significant in this moment

00:01:17.120 --> 00:01:18.870 align:middle line:90%
in time.

00:01:18.870 --> 00:01:20.787 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And it is
important, isn't it?

00:01:20.787 --> 00:01:22.370 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: I'll make
the case, George,

00:01:22.370 --> 00:01:25.850 align:middle line:84%
that creativity
is the most vital,

00:01:25.850 --> 00:01:29.000 align:middle line:84%
or one of the most vital,
of all human traits.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:29.960 align:middle line:90%
Think about it.

00:01:29.960 --> 00:01:31.850 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And give us
your definition, Matt,

00:01:31.850 --> 00:01:32.828 align:middle line:90%
of creativity.

00:01:32.828 --> 00:01:34.370 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: OK, fair
enough, because I

00:01:34.370 --> 00:01:40.190 align:middle line:84%
was going to say it's applicable
to the creation of civilization

00:01:40.190 --> 00:01:45.740 align:middle line:84%
from Shakespeare to every
medical innovation we've got.

00:01:45.740 --> 00:01:49.040 align:middle line:84%
But your point's
actually well taken.

00:01:49.040 --> 00:01:53.760 align:middle line:84%
Creativity, in my definition,
need not be nearly that grand.

00:01:53.760 --> 00:01:56.770 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, creativity is
highly applicable to almost all

00:01:56.770 --> 00:01:57.570 align:middle line:90%
of us.

00:01:57.570 --> 00:01:59.090 align:middle line:90%
Here's how I define it.

00:01:59.090 --> 00:02:03.380 align:middle line:84%
I define creativity
as something new

00:02:03.380 --> 00:02:05.900 align:middle line:90%
that makes some contribution.

00:02:05.900 --> 00:02:09.080 align:middle line:84%
So let me tell you how
modest that could be.

00:02:09.080 --> 00:02:13.040 align:middle line:84%
Have you ever walked into the
kitchen, opened the fridge,

00:02:13.040 --> 00:02:16.070 align:middle line:84%
and discovered three
ingredients are left?

00:02:16.070 --> 00:02:16.910 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:02:16.910 --> 00:02:18.920 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: And you've somehow
made something of that.

00:02:18.920 --> 00:02:19.790 align:middle line:90%
Or do you just order out?

00:02:19.790 --> 00:02:21.650 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You made your
peanut butter sandwich.

00:02:21.650 --> 00:02:23.025 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: You
made your peanut--

00:02:23.025 --> 00:02:25.820 align:middle line:84%
and somewhere along the
line, some mom or dad

00:02:25.820 --> 00:02:28.370 align:middle line:84%
walked into the kitchen and
there were three ingredients,

00:02:28.370 --> 00:02:31.310 align:middle line:84%
and he or she put that thing
together and created a dinner

00:02:31.310 --> 00:02:32.150 align:middle line:90%
for the kids.

00:02:32.150 --> 00:02:36.200 align:middle line:84%
That is a very modest
form of creativity.

00:02:36.200 --> 00:02:39.890 align:middle line:84%
But the reason I bring
it up is that creativity

00:02:39.890 --> 00:02:43.733 align:middle line:84%
can span from the modest all
the way to the extraordinary--

00:02:43.733 --> 00:02:44.700 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: True.

00:02:44.700 --> 00:02:46.770 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: --those things
that change our world.

00:02:46.770 --> 00:02:50.750 align:middle line:84%
And this is a particularly
creative moment in time.

00:02:50.750 --> 00:02:52.830 align:middle line:84%
May I just touch on the
science of why that is?

00:02:52.830 --> 00:02:53.630 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:02:53.630 --> 00:02:57.390 align:middle line:10%
>>RICHTEL: So this
book, "Inspired,"

00:02:57.390 --> 00:02:58.950 align:middle line:10%
starts in Jerusalem.

00:02:58.950 --> 00:03:03.010 align:middle line:10%
And I started in Jerusalem
because I thought to myself,

00:03:03.010 --> 00:03:05.910 align:middle line:10%
well, so much of our
understanding of creation

00:03:05.910 --> 00:03:09.070 align:middle line:10%
itself comes from the stories
here, whether you believe them

00:03:09.070 --> 00:03:09.870 align:middle line:10%
or not--

00:03:09.870 --> 00:03:12.030 align:middle line:10%
the mythologies, the tales.

00:03:12.030 --> 00:03:13.238 align:middle line:90%
So much of it's rooted there.

00:03:13.238 --> 00:03:14.155 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's amazing.

00:03:14.155 --> 00:03:15.210 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: It's amazing.

00:03:15.210 --> 00:03:17.340 align:middle line:84%
But I learned
something incredible

00:03:17.340 --> 00:03:19.650 align:middle line:84%
about Jerusalem that
was not the reason I

00:03:19.650 --> 00:03:20.820 align:middle line:90%
went there to begin with.

00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:25.200 align:middle line:84%
Jerusalem had a population in
the year zero of about 500,000.

00:03:25.200 --> 00:03:26.852 align:middle line:84%
Does that sound big
or small to you?

00:03:26.852 --> 00:03:27.810 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: In those days?

00:03:27.810 --> 00:03:28.020 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Yeah.

00:03:28.020 --> 00:03:28.840 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Huge.

00:03:28.840 --> 00:03:29.640 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Huge.

00:03:29.640 --> 00:03:31.740 align:middle line:90%
It's a huge number, George.

00:03:31.740 --> 00:03:34.350 align:middle line:84%
And the upshot of it
being a huge number

00:03:34.350 --> 00:03:38.140 align:middle line:84%
is there are lots of people
talking to each other,

00:03:38.140 --> 00:03:39.390 align:middle line:90%
communicating.

00:03:39.390 --> 00:03:41.640 align:middle line:90%
In a way, it's an industry town.

00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:43.800 align:middle line:84%
At that time, the
industry is religion

00:03:43.800 --> 00:03:46.470 align:middle line:84%
and there's a lot of ideas
and a lot of competition.

00:03:46.470 --> 00:03:47.970 align:middle line:90%
Now, let's fast--

00:03:47.970 --> 00:03:49.840 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And no social media.

00:03:49.840 --> 00:03:50.640 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: True.

00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:51.420 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: No radio.

00:03:51.420 --> 00:03:51.720 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Right.

00:03:51.720 --> 00:03:52.980 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: No television.

00:03:52.980 --> 00:03:56.053 align:middle line:84%
The only way to
communicate is one on one.

00:03:56.053 --> 00:03:56.970 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: One on one.

00:03:56.970 --> 00:04:01.320 align:middle line:84%
Or standing on a stump, like
the prophets may have done,

00:04:01.320 --> 00:04:03.000 align:middle line:84%
and speaking to a
bunch of people,

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:06.810 align:middle line:84%
who, in turn, build on those
ideas, share those ideas.

00:04:06.810 --> 00:04:10.320 align:middle line:84%
You can think of a rock as
the original social media.

00:04:10.320 --> 00:04:12.930 align:middle line:84%
Not one you threw,
but one you stood on.

00:04:12.930 --> 00:04:15.510 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's why Jesus
might have been so popular--

00:04:15.510 --> 00:04:17.165 align:middle line:90%
the way he spoke to a crowd.

00:04:17.165 --> 00:04:18.040 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: That's it.

00:04:18.040 --> 00:04:21.060 align:middle line:84%
So in that respect, of course,
there was no social media.

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:24.030 align:middle line:84%
But there was a
socializing of media

00:04:24.030 --> 00:04:26.910 align:middle line:84%
at that time in a
very busy place.

00:04:26.910 --> 00:04:29.160 align:middle line:90%
Here's what we've learned since.

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:33.610 align:middle line:84%
The research and science will
bear out that over the years,

00:04:33.610 --> 00:04:37.260 align:middle line:84%
there have been these enclaves
of extraordinary creativity.

00:04:37.260 --> 00:04:42.330 align:middle line:84%
Paris, parts of Russia,
parts of Italy, Harlem, Los

00:04:42.330 --> 00:04:44.700 align:middle line:84%
Angeles with Hollywood--
you can go down the list.

00:04:44.700 --> 00:04:49.500 align:middle line:84%
But think of this moment in
time where anybody anywhere

00:04:49.500 --> 00:04:50.610 align:middle line:90%
can connect.

00:04:50.610 --> 00:04:53.580 align:middle line:84%
To your mind, how would
you rank that in terms

00:04:53.580 --> 00:04:55.770 align:middle line:90%
of its creative potential?

00:04:55.770 --> 00:04:57.270 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Very high.

00:04:57.270 --> 00:05:00.170 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: Maybe the
highest it's ever been.

00:05:00.170 --> 00:05:03.260 align:middle line:84%
The-- I don't want
to start boring--

00:05:03.260 --> 00:05:05.630 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I'm passing your
quiz no matter what, right?

00:05:05.630 --> 00:05:06.800 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Yeah, you are.

00:05:06.800 --> 00:05:09.040 align:middle line:84%
I'm troubled because
I came to stump you.

00:05:09.040 --> 00:05:10.040 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You're not yet.

00:05:10.040 --> 00:05:10.840 align:middle line:90%
But you might.

00:05:10.840 --> 00:05:11.723 align:middle line:90%
It's not over yet.

00:05:11.723 --> 00:05:13.640 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: Well, I don't
know any good trivia.

00:05:13.640 --> 00:05:14.970 align:middle line:90%
So it's a problem.

00:05:14.970 --> 00:05:16.050 align:middle line:90%
But this is interesting.

00:05:16.050 --> 00:05:19.125 align:middle line:84%
This is actually some really
not so interesting trivia,

00:05:19.125 --> 00:05:20.000 align:middle line:90%
but I'll throw it in.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.970 align:middle line:84%
The number of
international patents,

00:05:22.970 --> 00:05:26.630 align:middle line:84%
meaning patents applied for
by people across borders,

00:05:26.630 --> 00:05:27.890 align:middle line:90%
has exploded.

00:05:27.890 --> 00:05:30.000 align:middle line:84%
Now, how the heck are
those people communicating?

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:30.800 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:05:30.800 --> 00:05:34.640 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: The internet, the
phone, email, various apps.

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:35.780 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Social.

00:05:35.780 --> 00:05:37.220 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: All social.

00:05:37.220 --> 00:05:40.480 align:middle line:84%
Incredibly explosively
creative period.

00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:43.780 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I've never seen kids
pick up on technology so fast.

00:05:43.780 --> 00:05:44.620 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Yeah.

00:05:44.620 --> 00:05:45.820 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: At a young age.

00:05:45.820 --> 00:05:46.150 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Yeah.

00:05:46.150 --> 00:05:47.930 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: One year
old, two years old,

00:05:47.930 --> 00:05:49.640 align:middle line:84%
they know how to
play a smartphone.

00:05:49.640 --> 00:05:51.880 align:middle line:84%
I couldn't have done
that in those days.

00:05:51.880 --> 00:05:53.920 align:middle line:84%
What are they going
to be like when they

00:05:53.920 --> 00:05:55.420 align:middle line:90%
get into the creative state?

00:05:55.420 --> 00:05:57.430 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: Well,
first of all, they're

00:05:57.430 --> 00:06:00.850 align:middle line:84%
going to be able to feast on
this extraordinary connection.

00:06:00.850 --> 00:06:05.500 align:middle line:84%
But you've really asked a
very significant question

00:06:05.500 --> 00:06:09.340 align:middle line:84%
and let me see if it's OK
if I answer it this way.

00:06:09.340 --> 00:06:12.910 align:middle line:84%
Can I talk a little bit about
young people and creativity,

00:06:12.910 --> 00:06:15.610 align:middle line:84%
and what the science
tells us about how

00:06:15.610 --> 00:06:19.180 align:middle line:84%
creative young people
are and why we sometimes

00:06:19.180 --> 00:06:20.630 align:middle line:90%
lose that creativity as adults?

00:06:20.630 --> 00:06:21.430 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:06:21.430 --> 00:06:22.230 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: OK.

00:06:22.230 --> 00:06:28.420 align:middle line:84%
So, interestingly, researchers
in the '50s and '60s

00:06:28.420 --> 00:06:31.240 align:middle line:84%
started to really
ask about creativity.

00:06:31.240 --> 00:06:34.570 align:middle line:84%
And they started to
ask, are kids creative?

00:06:34.570 --> 00:06:36.250 align:middle line:90%
Do they lose creativity?

00:06:36.250 --> 00:06:37.120 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:40.480 align:middle line:84%
And they discovered something
called the fourth grade slump.

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:43.600 align:middle line:84%
Are your grandkids
in fourth grade yet?

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:45.130 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: One of them is, yes.

00:06:45.130 --> 00:06:46.330 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: And are
the others younger?

00:06:46.330 --> 00:06:47.260 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They're older.

00:06:47.260 --> 00:06:48.302 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: They're older.

00:06:48.302 --> 00:06:50.980 align:middle line:84%
Well, I don't think-- given your
family history of creativity,

00:06:50.980 --> 00:06:52.060 align:middle line:90%
I'm not too worried.

00:06:52.060 --> 00:06:54.370 align:middle line:84%
But here's what happens
in fourth grade.

00:06:54.370 --> 00:06:56.540 align:middle line:84%
It's incredible to
think about this.

00:06:56.540 --> 00:06:59.410 align:middle line:84%
Kids prior to the
age of fourth grade

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:04.480 align:middle line:84%
in this very seminal study
in the late '50s and '60s,

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:08.410 align:middle line:84%
turn out to get less
creative after fourth grade.

00:07:08.410 --> 00:07:09.550 align:middle line:90%
The measure of creativity--

00:07:09.550 --> 00:07:09.820 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Really?

00:07:09.820 --> 00:07:12.112 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: Yes, the measure
of creativity in this study

00:07:12.112 --> 00:07:15.550 align:middle line:84%
is how many random ideas
the kids come up with.

00:07:15.550 --> 00:07:18.280 align:middle line:84%
And they start
coming up with ideas

00:07:18.280 --> 00:07:22.780 align:middle line:84%
that are more cliched or more
accepted or have been come up

00:07:22.780 --> 00:07:24.160 align:middle line:90%
with before after fourth grade.

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:27.110 align:middle line:84%
Now, what's your guess
as to why that might be?

00:07:27.110 --> 00:07:29.850 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Oh, gosh,
society changes it.

00:07:29.850 --> 00:07:30.650 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Tell me.

00:07:30.650 --> 00:07:31.445 align:middle line:90%
Keep going.

00:07:31.445 --> 00:07:32.130 align:middle line:90%
I haven't stopped you yet.

00:07:32.130 --> 00:07:33.260 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: School changes it.

00:07:33.260 --> 00:07:34.610 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Boom.

00:07:34.610 --> 00:07:36.395 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to keep
trying to stump you.

00:07:36.395 --> 00:07:36.680 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I'm doing well.

00:07:36.680 --> 00:07:38.080 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: We'll get there.

00:07:38.080 --> 00:07:39.950 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, let me
show you something.

00:07:39.950 --> 00:07:43.310 align:middle line:84%
Emmy award-winning
composer Chris Spheeris

00:07:43.310 --> 00:07:46.910 align:middle line:84%
talks about young
people, creativity,

00:07:46.910 --> 00:07:51.240 align:middle line:84%
and how it diminishes, like
you're saying, in early years.

00:07:51.240 --> 00:07:52.040 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:07:52.040 --> 00:07:54.680 align:middle line:10%
- Up to the age of five,
we still have about 80%

00:07:54.680 --> 00:07:57.050 align:middle line:10%
of our creative potential
available to us.

00:07:57.050 --> 00:08:00.620 align:middle line:10%
And by the age of 12, when we
enter school at kindergarten,

00:08:00.620 --> 00:08:03.060 align:middle line:10%
it's diminished down to 2%.

00:08:03.060 --> 00:08:03.860 align:middle line:90%
Shocking.

00:08:03.860 --> 00:08:05.930 align:middle line:84%
By 12, by the time we
hit pubescence, which

00:08:05.930 --> 00:08:07.190 align:middle line:90%
should be wildly creative.

00:08:07.190 --> 00:08:11.960 align:middle line:84%
- So can anyone out there
imagine that most of us--

00:08:11.960 --> 00:08:15.440 align:middle line:84%
most of them-- I have to not
include myself there really--

00:08:15.440 --> 00:08:18.410 align:middle line:84%
are operating on 2% of
our creative potential?

00:08:18.410 --> 00:08:20.750 align:middle line:84%
And I believe our
creative potential

00:08:20.750 --> 00:08:22.880 align:middle line:90%
is our full potential of being.

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:24.340 align:middle line:90%
That's everything that is.

00:08:24.340 --> 00:08:25.140 align:middle line:90%
- Everything.

00:08:25.140 --> 00:08:26.640 align:middle line:84%
- It's like taking
a beautiful plant

00:08:26.640 --> 00:08:30.935 align:middle line:84%
and cutting 98% of the
branches off and the leaves off

00:08:30.935 --> 00:08:33.260 align:middle line:90%
and expecting it to survive.

00:08:33.260 --> 00:08:34.940 align:middle line:90%
That's what we're doing.

00:08:34.940 --> 00:08:37.340 align:middle line:84%
- When we look at
society at large,

00:08:37.340 --> 00:08:39.679 align:middle line:84%
when we look at people around
us, as I said in the open,

00:08:39.679 --> 00:08:45.650 align:middle line:84%
we're seeing primarily
exhaustion, fear, defeatism.

00:08:45.650 --> 00:08:47.600 align:middle line:84%
We've been inundated
to the point where

00:08:47.600 --> 00:08:49.280 align:middle line:90%
we feel very small and less.

00:08:49.280 --> 00:08:50.990 align:middle line:90%
We don't have the energy.

00:08:50.990 --> 00:08:54.230 align:middle line:90%
How do you view--

00:08:54.230 --> 00:08:55.440 align:middle line:90%
- What a great word.

00:08:55.440 --> 00:08:56.240 align:middle line:90%
Energy.

00:08:56.240 --> 00:08:57.040 align:middle line:90%
- Yeah.

00:08:57.040 --> 00:09:00.000 align:middle line:84%
- Because I have a metaphor
that came to me about energy.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.120 align:middle line:84%
If you look at
what's popular now,

00:09:02.120 --> 00:09:05.000 align:middle line:84%
we're starting to
move our energy source

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:09.590 align:middle line:84%
from finite fossil
fuel to almost infinite

00:09:09.590 --> 00:09:11.240 align:middle line:90%
solar or other sources.

00:09:11.240 --> 00:09:12.740 align:middle line:84%
So let's look at
that as a metaphor.

00:09:12.740 --> 00:09:16.165 align:middle line:90%
- Potentially plentiful.

00:09:16.165 --> 00:09:17.540 align:middle line:84%
- The reason we're
getting tired,

00:09:17.540 --> 00:09:20.270 align:middle line:84%
exhausted, frustrated, cut
out, alienated, all that stuff,

00:09:20.270 --> 00:09:23.820 align:middle line:84%
is because we are tapping into
our ego consciousness for fuel.

00:09:23.820 --> 00:09:24.620 align:middle line:90%
- Yes.

00:09:24.620 --> 00:09:27.680 align:middle line:84%
- And that seems to
be running our society

00:09:27.680 --> 00:09:30.080 align:middle line:84%
in a way that makes
us feel old and tired

00:09:30.080 --> 00:09:31.610 align:middle line:84%
and all those things
you mentioned.

00:09:31.610 --> 00:09:34.220 align:middle line:84%
Now, there is an
alternate energy source.

00:09:34.220 --> 00:09:36.200 align:middle line:84%
It's tapping into
our inspiration.

00:09:36.200 --> 00:09:40.700 align:middle line:84%
It's tapping into our real
fuel, which is our innocence.

00:09:40.700 --> 00:09:42.950 align:middle line:84%
It's our state of
awareness and presence.

00:09:42.950 --> 00:09:44.580 align:middle line:90%
It's all these things.

00:09:44.580 --> 00:09:45.980 align:middle line:90%
It's our creativity.

00:09:45.980 --> 00:09:50.420 align:middle line:84%
If we tap into that, as opposed
to our own self-concept--

00:09:50.420 --> 00:09:52.880 align:middle line:84%
and I mean, here's
the way I look at it.

00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:54.580 align:middle line:84%
Our culture, to me,
looks like this-- it

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:57.110 align:middle line:84%
looks like we're all
at a Halloween party

00:09:57.110 --> 00:09:59.695 align:middle line:84%
and we're believing that
the person is the costume.

00:09:59.695 --> 00:10:01.070 align:middle line:84%
And we're forgetting
that there's

00:10:01.070 --> 00:10:02.510 align:middle line:90%
a person behind the costume.

00:10:02.510 --> 00:10:05.000 align:middle line:84%
And that's how I
see ego awareness is

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:08.000 align:middle line:90%
in such a strong illusion.

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:10.490 align:middle line:84%
And we're forgetting
that there is a pure soul

00:10:10.490 --> 00:10:14.150 align:middle line:90%
behind the masks we wear.

00:10:14.150 --> 00:10:17.210 align:middle line:90%
So how do we get back, right?

00:10:17.210 --> 00:10:20.540 align:middle line:84%
We do what we can to connect
to our innocence, which

00:10:20.540 --> 00:10:24.200 align:middle line:84%
happens through enthusiasm,
and passion, and compassion,

00:10:24.200 --> 00:10:25.250 align:middle line:90%
and love.

00:10:25.250 --> 00:10:26.582 align:middle line:90%
[END PLAYBACK]

00:10:26.582 --> 00:10:28.290 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What do you
think of that, Matt?

00:10:28.290 --> 00:10:31.450 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: First of all,
I'm jealous of his hair.

00:10:31.450 --> 00:10:32.840 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:10:32.840 --> 00:10:34.263 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Eh, it is what it is.

00:10:34.263 --> 00:10:35.430 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: It is what it is.

00:10:35.430 --> 00:10:39.120 align:middle line:84%
Look, the science will
bear out a lot of what

00:10:39.120 --> 00:10:41.160 align:middle line:90%
those two folks are saying.

00:10:41.160 --> 00:10:44.370 align:middle line:84%
If you go back to
fourth grade, there's

00:10:44.370 --> 00:10:45.930 align:middle line:84%
something interesting--
you alluded

00:10:45.930 --> 00:10:49.220 align:middle line:84%
to school-- there's something
interesting that happens.

00:10:49.220 --> 00:10:53.520 align:middle line:84%
Kids have grown up
hearing the following--

00:10:53.520 --> 00:10:58.720 align:middle line:84%
don't cross the street, don't
pick your nose and eat it,

00:10:58.720 --> 00:11:00.180 align:middle line:90%
don't eat food off the floor.

00:11:00.180 --> 00:11:01.410 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Don't, don't, don't.

00:11:01.410 --> 00:11:03.660 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: And there's a
good reason for that, George.

00:11:03.660 --> 00:11:06.532 align:middle line:84%
There's actually-- I'm
not trying to judge this.

00:11:06.532 --> 00:11:08.490 align:middle line:84%
I'm trying to put it
through a scientific lens.

00:11:08.490 --> 00:11:11.190 align:middle line:84%
The good reason is we're
trying to teach kids

00:11:11.190 --> 00:11:16.260 align:middle line:84%
that there's many rules
they must follow in order

00:11:16.260 --> 00:11:17.430 align:middle line:90%
to survive.

00:11:17.430 --> 00:11:19.800 align:middle line:84%
I would point out that
what the kid also does

00:11:19.800 --> 00:11:24.690 align:middle line:84%
is begin to internalize the
idea that no comes before yes.

00:11:24.690 --> 00:11:27.570 align:middle line:84%
And creativity,
as I get into what

00:11:27.570 --> 00:11:31.200 align:middle line:84%
I consider to be the
wonders and mysteries of it,

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:33.780 align:middle line:90%
is an act of saying yes.

00:11:33.780 --> 00:11:38.770 align:middle line:84%
It's an act of saying yes
to things that may be scary.

00:11:38.770 --> 00:11:40.980 align:middle line:84%
We've talked about
this on your show.

00:11:40.980 --> 00:11:45.440 align:middle line:84%
Do you want to go into the
creativity vomit research?

00:11:45.440 --> 00:11:46.910 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Vomit research?

00:11:46.910 --> 00:11:48.510 align:middle line:90%
What the heck is that?

00:11:48.510 --> 00:11:51.380 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: OK, so this--

00:11:51.380 --> 00:11:55.010 align:middle line:84%
again, this book is a deep
dive into how creativity works

00:11:55.010 --> 00:11:56.790 align:middle line:90%
and the real science of it.

00:11:56.790 --> 00:12:00.710 align:middle line:84%
And the first thing that
I had to grapple with

00:12:00.710 --> 00:12:04.580 align:middle line:84%
is that creativity
oftentimes eludes us

00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:07.390 align:middle line:90%
because we are terrified of it.

00:12:07.390 --> 00:12:09.213 align:middle line:90%
One of the best studies--

00:12:09.213 --> 00:12:10.630 align:middle line:84%
are you ready for
the vomit study?

00:12:10.630 --> 00:12:11.510 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yep.

00:12:11.510 --> 00:12:12.310 align:middle line:90%
Fire away.

00:12:12.310 --> 00:12:13.720 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Here we go.

00:12:13.720 --> 00:12:20.890 align:middle line:84%
A researcher says, we all say
we love creativity, but do we

00:12:20.890 --> 00:12:23.740 align:middle line:90%
actually really like creativity?

00:12:23.740 --> 00:12:26.950 align:middle line:84%
He said-- I call this
the smart dumb question.

00:12:26.950 --> 00:12:29.050 align:middle line:90%
We take something for granted.

00:12:29.050 --> 00:12:32.200 align:middle line:84%
And he goes out and he
does this study where he

00:12:32.200 --> 00:12:34.690 align:middle line:90%
uses a subconscious bias test.

00:12:34.690 --> 00:12:37.330 align:middle line:84%
This is the test that
we use to find out

00:12:37.330 --> 00:12:40.660 align:middle line:84%
if the thing we say about,
say, someone of another race,

00:12:40.660 --> 00:12:43.420 align:middle line:84%
or someone walking
across the street,

00:12:43.420 --> 00:12:46.173 align:middle line:84%
is if we actually feel
the way we say we feel.

00:12:46.173 --> 00:12:47.590 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Or religion
or something.

00:12:47.590 --> 00:12:49.090 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: All of the above.

00:12:49.090 --> 00:12:52.863 align:middle line:84%
Do we harbor some biases
we have not expressed?

00:12:52.863 --> 00:12:54.280 align:middle line:84%
So we asked a bunch
of people, how

00:12:54.280 --> 00:12:55.720 align:middle line:90%
do you feel about creativity?

00:12:55.720 --> 00:12:58.100 align:middle line:84%
And they make these
associations, George.

00:12:58.100 --> 00:13:00.010 align:middle line:84%
What do you think
they say they think?

00:13:00.010 --> 00:13:02.440 align:middle line:84%
How do you think they say
they feel about creativity?

00:13:02.440 --> 00:13:04.370 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I think they
think they're spot on.

00:13:04.370 --> 00:13:05.912 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: They
think it's wonderful.

00:13:05.912 --> 00:13:08.830 align:middle line:84%
They're like,
creativity is associated

00:13:08.830 --> 00:13:12.310 align:middle line:84%
with rainbows and puppy dogs
and chocolate ice cream.

00:13:12.310 --> 00:13:13.480 align:middle line:90%
All this great stuff.

00:13:13.480 --> 00:13:16.120 align:middle line:84%
But then they run a
subconscious bias test,

00:13:16.120 --> 00:13:17.800 align:middle line:84%
which involves
showing some images

00:13:17.800 --> 00:13:21.260 align:middle line:84%
and picking up how
people really feel.

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:28.130 align:middle line:84%
Guess what, vomit, toxins,
poison, even death.

00:13:28.130 --> 00:13:29.660 align:middle line:90%
Now, what's going on?

00:13:29.660 --> 00:13:31.160 align:middle line:90%
Do you have a guess?

00:13:31.160 --> 00:13:32.840 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Why they
have that flip-flop?

00:13:32.840 --> 00:13:35.360 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: Why do
they consciously say,

00:13:35.360 --> 00:13:39.150 align:middle line:84%
I love creativity, but
subconsciously say,

00:13:39.150 --> 00:13:40.620 align:middle line:90%
that scares the heck out of me.

00:13:40.620 --> 00:13:42.920 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Because sometime
when they were smaller,

00:13:42.920 --> 00:13:46.550 align:middle line:84%
something happened to
them with creativity

00:13:46.550 --> 00:13:48.680 align:middle line:90%
and it distorted their views.

00:13:48.680 --> 00:13:52.730 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: That's a great
guess, and that's a piece of it.

00:13:52.730 --> 00:13:55.290 align:middle line:84%
There are two
other vital pieces.

00:13:55.290 --> 00:13:58.250 align:middle line:90%
Here's what creativity does.

00:13:58.250 --> 00:14:01.130 align:middle line:84%
One, it takes an
immense risk, which

00:14:01.130 --> 00:14:02.660 align:middle line:90%
is what you're alluding to.

00:14:02.660 --> 00:14:05.480 align:middle line:84%
If you come up with an idea
someone hasn't come up with

00:14:05.480 --> 00:14:09.110 align:middle line:84%
before, only in retrospect
do we say, great idea,

00:14:09.110 --> 00:14:10.610 align:middle line:90%
Elon Musk changed the world.

00:14:10.610 --> 00:14:15.260 align:middle line:84%
But how many Elon Musks were
there that failed miserably,

00:14:15.260 --> 00:14:18.860 align:middle line:84%
that had terrible financial
trouble, whose marriage has

00:14:18.860 --> 00:14:20.980 align:middle line:90%
dissolved, that were drinking?

00:14:20.980 --> 00:14:21.970 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Many, many.

00:14:21.970 --> 00:14:22.770 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Many.

00:14:22.770 --> 00:14:24.650 align:middle line:90%
Many more than succeeded.

00:14:24.650 --> 00:14:26.480 align:middle line:84%
So the science of
creativity will

00:14:26.480 --> 00:14:31.490 align:middle line:84%
show it is an immense risk
for those who actually try it,

00:14:31.490 --> 00:14:33.090 align:middle line:90%
and, therefore, scary.

00:14:33.090 --> 00:14:35.960 align:middle line:84%
And there's a second reason
creativity, the science shows,

00:14:35.960 --> 00:14:36.980 align:middle line:90%
is so scary.

00:14:36.980 --> 00:14:41.780 align:middle line:84%
And that's because, what happens
when creativity succeeds?

00:14:41.780 --> 00:14:44.330 align:middle line:84%
What's your take on
why would that be scary

00:14:44.330 --> 00:14:45.740 align:middle line:90%
if creativity succeeds?

00:14:45.740 --> 00:14:48.263 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Because people might
not know how to handle it.

00:14:48.263 --> 00:14:50.180 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: People don't
know how to handle it.

00:14:50.180 --> 00:14:54.240 align:middle line:84%
And worst of all are the people
don't know how to handle it

00:14:54.240 --> 00:14:56.835 align:middle line:84%
who were invested
in the prior thing.

00:14:56.835 --> 00:14:57.710 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Interesting.

00:14:57.710 --> 00:15:00.180 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: And that
is so much of society.

00:15:00.180 --> 00:15:02.438 align:middle line:84%
So get this-- well,
let's just take Elon Musk

00:15:02.438 --> 00:15:03.980 align:middle line:84%
because we've been
talking about him.

00:15:03.980 --> 00:15:08.160 align:middle line:84%
All this wonderful
electric vehicles--

00:15:08.160 --> 00:15:10.500 align:middle line:84%
again, no political or
partisan judgment here-- but

00:15:10.500 --> 00:15:12.540 align:middle line:84%
if you're in the
oil industry, if you

00:15:12.540 --> 00:15:15.810 align:middle line:84%
run General Motors, if
you're a coal miner,

00:15:15.810 --> 00:15:18.150 align:middle line:90%
that could be a serious problem.

00:15:18.150 --> 00:15:22.570 align:middle line:84%
One person's innovation
is another person's death.

00:15:22.570 --> 00:15:23.873 align:middle line:90%
And that's why--

00:15:23.873 --> 00:15:24.915 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Absolutely true.

00:15:24.915 --> 00:15:26.940 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: --creativity
is terrifying.

00:15:26.940 --> 00:15:29.820 align:middle line:84%
For us to be creative, we've
got to understand the terror.

00:15:29.820 --> 00:15:32.400 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We have lots of truck
drivers who listen to my radio

00:15:32.400 --> 00:15:32.680 align:middle line:90%
show--

00:15:32.680 --> 00:15:33.030 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Yes.

00:15:33.030 --> 00:15:33.630 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --coast to coast.

00:15:33.630 --> 00:15:34.430 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Yes.

00:15:34.430 --> 00:15:36.770 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I am opposed
to driverless trucks.

00:15:36.770 --> 00:15:37.770 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: There you go.

00:15:37.770 --> 00:15:39.460 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They are
working on them.

00:15:39.460 --> 00:15:40.800 align:middle line:90%
They are testing them.

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:42.730 align:middle line:90%
It's going to happen.

00:15:42.730 --> 00:15:46.260 align:middle line:84%
I don't want our truck
drivers out of jobs.

00:15:46.260 --> 00:15:48.693 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: This is the very--
we had this conversation,

00:15:48.693 --> 00:15:49.860 align:middle line:90%
and you mentioned it before.

00:15:49.860 --> 00:15:55.780 align:middle line:84%
And it's the perfect example of
where one person's innovation

00:15:55.780 --> 00:15:58.163 align:middle line:90%
is another person's job loss.

00:15:58.163 --> 00:16:00.580 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But I want to talk
about Jeff Bezos for a moment.

00:16:00.580 --> 00:16:04.180 align:middle line:84%
In your opinion, when he
came up with this concept,

00:16:04.180 --> 00:16:07.030 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to sell
books on the internet,

00:16:07.030 --> 00:16:09.670 align:middle line:84%
people don't have to go
to bookstores anymore,

00:16:09.670 --> 00:16:11.600 align:middle line:84%
and I'm doing it
out of my garage--

00:16:11.600 --> 00:16:12.400 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Yes.

00:16:12.400 --> 00:16:14.170 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --do you
think he envisioned

00:16:14.170 --> 00:16:17.770 align:middle line:84%
having the world's largest
online retail establishment?

00:16:17.770 --> 00:16:19.090 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: This is what I--

00:16:19.090 --> 00:16:20.590 align:middle line:84%
it's a great
question and I can't

00:16:20.590 --> 00:16:23.710 align:middle line:84%
say because it's one of
the handful of really

00:16:23.710 --> 00:16:26.350 align:middle line:84%
luminaries in this space I
haven't talked to personally.

00:16:26.350 --> 00:16:31.600 align:middle line:84%
But I actually do have an answer
based on the science, which

00:16:31.600 --> 00:16:36.160 align:middle line:84%
is many of these great
creators don't really

00:16:36.160 --> 00:16:39.820 align:middle line:84%
start with the big
vision and the end game

00:16:39.820 --> 00:16:40.690 align:middle line:90%
they start out with.

00:16:40.690 --> 00:16:43.420 align:middle line:84%
They start out with
moments of insight.

00:16:43.420 --> 00:16:44.920 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Do they luck into it?

00:16:44.920 --> 00:16:46.870 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: They work
their way into it

00:16:46.870 --> 00:16:51.640 align:middle line:84%
by a series of creations
that follow one on the next.

00:16:51.640 --> 00:16:54.460 align:middle line:84%
Well, what I'm
getting at is, George,

00:16:54.460 --> 00:16:57.490 align:middle line:84%
I think a lot of
creative people both

00:16:57.490 --> 00:17:00.820 align:middle line:84%
have a point on the
horizon and the thing

00:17:00.820 --> 00:17:02.270 align:middle line:90%
that's in front of them.

00:17:02.270 --> 00:17:05.410 align:middle line:84%
But when they're really
driven and creative,

00:17:05.410 --> 00:17:09.790 align:middle line:84%
each step of the way becomes
its own creative pursuit.

00:17:09.790 --> 00:17:12.040 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Tell me if
this is creative.

00:17:12.040 --> 00:17:13.130 align:middle line:90%
I'm at an event one day.

00:17:13.130 --> 00:17:13.930 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Yes.

00:17:13.930 --> 00:17:15.763 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And a lady
comes up to me and says,

00:17:15.763 --> 00:17:17.470 align:middle line:90%
you got to help me.

00:17:17.470 --> 00:17:18.670 align:middle line:90%
I said, well, what's wrong?

00:17:18.670 --> 00:17:20.170 align:middle line:90%
What can I do for you?

00:17:20.170 --> 00:17:23.365 align:middle line:84%
She said, I went on a
date last week with a guy

00:17:23.365 --> 00:17:26.740 align:middle line:84%
and I started talking
about UFOs and Bigfoot.

00:17:26.740 --> 00:17:28.089 align:middle line:90%
And we were having dinner.

00:17:28.089 --> 00:17:29.870 align:middle line:90%
And he said, what?

00:17:29.870 --> 00:17:32.230 align:middle line:90%
And I said, UFOs, Bigfoot.

00:17:32.230 --> 00:17:34.000 align:middle line:90%
And he went, you're nuts.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:35.780 align:middle line:90%
He got up and left.

00:17:35.780 --> 00:17:37.420 align:middle line:84%
You got to do
something for people

00:17:37.420 --> 00:17:39.880 align:middle line:90%
like us who understand this.

00:17:39.880 --> 00:17:41.560 align:middle line:84%
And I came back
and said, you know

00:17:41.560 --> 00:17:45.592 align:middle line:84%
what, I've got this
vehicle of this radio show.

00:17:45.592 --> 00:17:47.050 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to come
up with something

00:17:47.050 --> 00:17:49.780 align:middle line:90%
called paranormaldate.com.

00:17:49.780 --> 00:17:52.418 align:middle line:90%
And it is immensely successful.

00:17:52.418 --> 00:17:53.710 align:middle line:90%
But I matched people together--

