00:28:17.370 --> 00:28:20.460 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Creativity
doesn't come to everybody.

00:28:20.460 --> 00:28:22.120 align:middle line:90%
Why not, Matt?

00:28:22.120 --> 00:28:25.260 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: I think the why not
is because we block it out.

00:28:25.260 --> 00:28:29.170 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to
offer the simplest

00:28:29.170 --> 00:28:32.560 align:middle line:84%
way of thinking about how to
let it in that I've come across.

00:28:32.560 --> 00:28:35.050 align:middle line:84%
I'll share one of my
own to give people

00:28:35.050 --> 00:28:39.490 align:middle line:84%
a sense of what creativity feels
like if they feel like they

00:28:39.490 --> 00:28:40.960 align:middle line:90%
don't have it in them.

00:28:40.960 --> 00:28:44.830 align:middle line:10%
Because this book
makes the case,

00:28:44.830 --> 00:28:47.890 align:middle line:10%
again, based not
on woo-woo stuff,

00:28:47.890 --> 00:28:49.850 align:middle line:10%
but on hard-core science.

00:28:49.850 --> 00:28:50.650 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:28:50.650 --> 00:28:51.740 align:middle line:10%
Very practical.

00:28:51.740 --> 00:28:55.750 align:middle line:10%
>>RICHTEL: Very deeply
practical that every one of us

00:28:55.750 --> 00:28:58.250 align:middle line:10%
has creativity inside.

00:28:58.250 --> 00:29:05.060 align:middle line:84%
So when I was a kid, we
had not a ton of money.

00:29:05.060 --> 00:29:08.830 align:middle line:84%
And I would go to bed at night
and I would dream that someone

00:29:08.830 --> 00:29:10.120 align:middle line:90%
had given me a five--

00:29:10.120 --> 00:29:12.460 align:middle line:84%
not dream-- fantasize
that someone had given me

00:29:12.460 --> 00:29:16.310 align:middle line:84%
a $500 gift certificate to the
sporting goods store, George.

00:29:16.310 --> 00:29:17.110 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Aha.

00:29:17.110 --> 00:29:19.390 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: And I had a
basket in front of me

00:29:19.390 --> 00:29:21.250 align:middle line:90%
and I had to fill it with stuff.

00:29:21.250 --> 00:29:26.020 align:middle line:84%
And I would go to bed at night
and I would fill it with things

00:29:26.020 --> 00:29:27.250 align:middle line:90%
and fall asleep.

00:29:27.250 --> 00:29:30.290 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: A baseball
glove, whatever.

00:29:30.290 --> 00:29:32.690 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: I would submit
to you that before people

00:29:32.690 --> 00:29:36.650 align:middle line:84%
go to bed, or at other times
when they're very relaxed,

00:29:36.650 --> 00:29:38.870 align:middle line:90%
their mind wanders.

00:29:38.870 --> 00:29:42.410 align:middle line:84%
I think it's one of the most
common things people do.

00:29:42.410 --> 00:29:45.070 align:middle line:90%
Here's what they don't realize.

00:29:45.070 --> 00:29:49.880 align:middle line:84%
When I was telling myself
that story, I was a writer.

00:29:49.880 --> 00:29:54.330 align:middle line:84%
Any time, George, your mind
wanders, you are a writer.

00:29:54.330 --> 00:29:56.010 align:middle line:90%
You are an entrepreneur.

00:29:56.010 --> 00:29:58.860 align:middle line:84%
You might tell yourself
the lyrics for a song.

00:29:58.860 --> 00:30:01.400 align:middle line:84%
But people don't credit
themselves enough,

00:30:01.400 --> 00:30:03.905 align:middle line:84%
and often just dismiss
those as mind-wandering.

00:30:03.905 --> 00:30:04.780 align:middle line:90%
Does that make sense?

00:30:04.780 --> 00:30:05.697 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yes, it does.

00:30:05.697 --> 00:30:09.500 align:middle line:84%
But I think what you're
saying, your dream state

00:30:09.500 --> 00:30:13.160 align:middle line:84%
is one of the most creative
areas that we have.

00:30:13.160 --> 00:30:15.170 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: The
mind-wandering state,

00:30:15.170 --> 00:30:19.380 align:middle line:84%
the edge of consciousness,
it used to be that--

00:30:19.380 --> 00:30:20.510 align:middle line:90%
and I'm going to--

00:30:20.510 --> 00:30:23.060 align:middle line:84%
I think it's Edison,
and, if I'm not mistaken,

00:30:23.060 --> 00:30:27.650 align:middle line:90%
Salvador Dali, used to do this--

00:30:27.650 --> 00:30:30.510 align:middle line:84%
it's in the book, if
I've mistaken the artist.

00:30:30.510 --> 00:30:32.480 align:middle line:90%
But I think these are they--

00:30:32.480 --> 00:30:35.930 align:middle line:84%
they would take a nap
every day, or occasionally,

00:30:35.930 --> 00:30:39.330 align:middle line:84%
with a rock in their
hand or a heavy object.

00:30:39.330 --> 00:30:41.810 align:middle line:84%
And as they would
nod off to sleep,

00:30:41.810 --> 00:30:44.630 align:middle line:84%
the object would
fall from their hands

00:30:44.630 --> 00:30:49.580 align:middle line:84%
and they would awaken from
the sound and have ideas.

00:30:49.580 --> 00:30:50.550 align:middle line:90%
And they would call--

00:30:50.550 --> 00:30:51.290 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Interesting technique.

00:30:51.290 --> 00:30:52.998 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: It's an
interesting technique.

00:30:52.998 --> 00:30:56.010 align:middle line:84%
The researchers call it
a hypnagogic test state.

00:30:56.010 --> 00:30:56.810 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: State.

00:30:56.810 --> 00:30:57.950 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Thank you.

00:30:57.950 --> 00:30:58.783 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Absolutely.

00:30:58.783 --> 00:30:59.610 align:middle line:90%
It works.

00:30:59.610 --> 00:31:00.410 align:middle line:90%
It works.

00:31:00.410 --> 00:31:03.080 align:middle line:84%
What is the spice rack
theory of creativity?

00:31:03.080 --> 00:31:06.340 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: So this goes
back to that very notion

00:31:06.340 --> 00:31:11.230 align:middle line:84%
we were talking about earlier
with your paranormal dating

00:31:11.230 --> 00:31:12.100 align:middle line:90%
site.

00:31:12.100 --> 00:31:18.130 align:middle line:84%
Inside George Noory's brain is
a whole bunch of information.

00:31:18.130 --> 00:31:20.530 align:middle line:84%
I think of the information
that each of us

00:31:20.530 --> 00:31:24.250 align:middle line:84%
contains and gather over
the years as a spice

00:31:24.250 --> 00:31:29.520 align:middle line:84%
rack of potential
contributors to creativity.

00:31:29.520 --> 00:31:31.110 align:middle line:90%
You go into your kitchen.

00:31:31.110 --> 00:31:32.940 align:middle line:90%
You open the spice rack.

00:31:32.940 --> 00:31:36.270 align:middle line:84%
The number of things you
can create for dinner

00:31:36.270 --> 00:31:39.030 align:middle line:84%
depends entirely on
the number of spices

00:31:39.030 --> 00:31:41.510 align:middle line:90%
that you have available to you.

00:31:41.510 --> 00:31:45.200 align:middle line:84%
Similarly, your
ability to be creative,

00:31:45.200 --> 00:31:47.930 align:middle line:84%
depends on your ability--
not you, George,

00:31:47.930 --> 00:31:48.770 align:middle line:90%
but one's ability--

00:31:48.770 --> 00:31:49.687 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I understand.

00:31:49.687 --> 00:31:51.800 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: --depends
on one's ability

00:31:51.800 --> 00:31:54.290 align:middle line:90%
to bring in a lot of material.

00:31:54.290 --> 00:31:56.180 align:middle line:90%
Why do I mention this?

00:31:56.180 --> 00:31:59.270 align:middle line:84%
We live in a period
of time, George,

00:31:59.270 --> 00:32:03.470 align:middle line:84%
where it is very tempting
to shut out information

00:32:03.470 --> 00:32:06.770 align:middle line:84%
because it feels too
chaotic, to choose

00:32:06.770 --> 00:32:08.750 align:middle line:90%
a position that is rigid--

00:32:08.750 --> 00:32:10.160 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And safe.

00:32:10.160 --> 00:32:11.840 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: --and safe.

00:32:11.840 --> 00:32:14.430 align:middle line:84%
There are lots of
reasons to do that.

00:32:14.430 --> 00:32:18.950 align:middle line:84%
But to be creative, as your
other guests have alluded

00:32:18.950 --> 00:32:22.940 align:middle line:84%
to in these wonderful
videos, depends, in part,

00:32:22.940 --> 00:32:27.050 align:middle line:84%
on opening yourself up to
all the spices around you,

00:32:27.050 --> 00:32:31.220 align:middle line:84%
the emotions and ideas, that
scary though they might be,

00:32:31.220 --> 00:32:34.880 align:middle line:84%
are the foodstuff of the
next great dating site.

00:32:34.880 --> 00:32:36.230 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's true.

00:32:36.230 --> 00:32:37.190 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:32:37.190 --> 00:32:40.850 align:middle line:84%
Are there similar traits
of very creative people?

00:32:40.850 --> 00:32:44.190 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: Curiosity,
a willingness

00:32:44.190 --> 00:32:46.860 align:middle line:84%
to listen to yourself
and the ideas,

00:32:46.860 --> 00:32:49.380 align:middle line:84%
and a willingness
not to be so rigid,

00:32:49.380 --> 00:32:53.430 align:middle line:84%
and then a faith that the
idea that you come up with

00:32:53.430 --> 00:32:57.030 align:middle line:84%
deserves at least to
be shared in the world,

00:32:57.030 --> 00:32:58.770 align:middle line:90%
even though it might fail.

00:32:58.770 --> 00:33:02.930 align:middle line:84%
And I'll tell you a
great Einstein story.

00:33:02.930 --> 00:33:05.380 align:middle line:84%
Einstein comes to a
colleague and says--

00:33:05.380 --> 00:33:07.880 align:middle line:84%
you remember he wanted to find
the unified field theory that

00:33:07.880 --> 00:33:08.690 align:middle line:90%
would explain everything?

00:33:08.690 --> 00:33:09.680 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Absolutely.

00:33:09.680 --> 00:33:11.040 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: It was his dream.

00:33:11.040 --> 00:33:14.540 align:middle line:84%
He comes to a colleague
and he says, I've got it.

00:33:14.540 --> 00:33:18.020 align:middle line:84%
I've got the unified
field theory finally.

00:33:18.020 --> 00:33:19.670 align:middle line:84%
And he tells it
to his colleague.

00:33:19.670 --> 00:33:22.370 align:middle line:84%
And his colleague
says, well, Albert,

00:33:22.370 --> 00:33:24.560 align:middle line:84%
that's great, except
under that theory,

00:33:24.560 --> 00:33:25.835 align:middle line:90%
the universe can't exist.

00:33:25.835 --> 00:33:26.870 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

00:33:26.870 --> 00:33:27.920 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sorry, Albert.

00:33:27.920 --> 00:33:28.550 align:middle line:90%
>>RICHTEL: Sorry, Albert.

00:33:28.550 --> 00:33:29.425 align:middle line:90%
You missed this time.

00:33:29.425 --> 00:33:33.320 align:middle line:84%
You know what Albert Einstein
is known for among scholars

00:33:33.320 --> 00:33:34.280 align:middle line:90%
who study him?

00:33:34.280 --> 00:33:36.690 align:middle line:84%
He's known for his
number of failures.

00:33:36.690 --> 00:33:37.490 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Wow.

00:33:37.490 --> 00:33:39.175 align:middle line:84%
If the poor guy had
a computer, do you

00:33:39.175 --> 00:33:40.550 align:middle line:84%
know how good he
would have been?

00:33:40.550 --> 00:33:41.350 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:41.350 --> 00:33:43.170 align:middle line:84%
>>RICHTEL: He would
have been good, George.

00:33:43.170 --> 00:33:45.570 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Gaia's got a show
called "Inspirations."

00:33:45.570 --> 00:33:50.300 align:middle line:84%
Chris Attwood was discussing the
power of the creative process.

00:33:50.300 --> 00:33:51.100 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:33:51.100 --> 00:33:54.400 align:middle line:10%
- That's really one of the
powers that ritual has,

00:33:54.400 --> 00:33:57.550 align:middle line:10%
is that it allows us to
be able to get in a space

00:33:57.550 --> 00:34:00.140 align:middle line:10%
where we can create what we
choose to have in our life.

00:34:00.140 --> 00:34:03.070 align:middle line:84%
- How can you use it to
really improve your life?

00:34:03.070 --> 00:34:06.810 align:middle line:84%
What situation would it work
with to improve your life?

00:34:06.810 --> 00:34:11.889 align:middle line:84%
- Yeah, so the ritual
has many purposes

00:34:11.889 --> 00:34:13.570 align:middle line:84%
from many different
perspectives.

00:34:13.570 --> 00:34:16.969 align:middle line:84%
And of course, improve
is a relative term.

00:34:16.969 --> 00:34:20.020 align:middle line:84%
But what you'll see
is, in every industry,

00:34:20.020 --> 00:34:22.239 align:middle line:84%
people who are really,
really successful

00:34:22.239 --> 00:34:24.880 align:middle line:84%
have all incorporated
rituals into their life

00:34:24.880 --> 00:34:26.239 align:middle line:90%
in one way or another.

00:34:26.239 --> 00:34:29.080 align:middle line:84%
And so you see
that sports players

00:34:29.080 --> 00:34:32.080 align:middle line:84%
use rituals to improve
their performance,

00:34:32.080 --> 00:34:35.350 align:middle line:84%
to be able to get their mind
into the game as it were.

00:34:35.350 --> 00:34:37.870 align:middle line:84%
The musicians and
artists use rituals

00:34:37.870 --> 00:34:39.820 align:middle line:84%
to spark their
creativity so that they

00:34:39.820 --> 00:34:43.540 align:middle line:84%
can be the best at
what their passion is.

00:34:43.540 --> 00:34:47.110 align:middle line:84%
Business leaders use rituals
to create cohesive teams

00:34:47.110 --> 00:34:49.989 align:middle line:84%
and to create strong
corporate cultures.

00:34:49.989 --> 00:34:52.120 align:middle line:84%
Celebrities use
rituals to create

00:34:52.120 --> 00:34:54.860 align:middle line:84%
balance between their personal
lives and their work lives.

00:34:54.860 --> 00:34:57.400 align:middle line:84%
And for me, all of those
are improving your life.

00:34:57.400 --> 00:34:59.830 align:middle line:84%
Rituals help you manage
your time, your energy

00:34:59.830 --> 00:35:01.150 align:middle line:90%
and your thinking.

00:35:01.150 --> 00:35:02.690 align:middle line:90%
And all of us need that, right?

00:35:02.690 --> 00:35:03.490 align:middle line:90%
- Yes.

00:35:03.490 --> 00:35:07.120 align:middle line:84%
- And so the rituals are a
way of bringing ourselves back

00:35:07.120 --> 00:35:08.140 align:middle line:90%
to ourselves.

00:35:08.140 --> 00:35:11.830 align:middle line:84%
And it could be by
establishing a routine

00:35:11.830 --> 00:35:15.040 align:middle line:84%
in our life, a daily
set of rituals,

00:35:15.040 --> 00:35:18.100 align:middle line:84%
so that we have time for
exercise, for stretching,

00:35:18.100 --> 00:35:20.530 align:middle line:84%
for breathing, for
meditation, or prayer.

00:35:20.530 --> 00:35:21.655 align:middle line:90%
- Oh, so those are rituals.

00:35:21.655 --> 00:35:22.655 align:middle line:90%
- Those are all rituals.

00:35:22.655 --> 00:35:23.500 align:middle line:90%
- Oh, OK.

00:35:23.500 --> 00:35:27.160 align:middle line:84%
- And then as we
come into our day,

00:35:27.160 --> 00:35:32.680 align:middle line:84%
having had that sequence of
actively engaging our body

00:35:32.680 --> 00:35:35.680 align:middle line:84%
and then quieting our
mind and our body as well,

00:35:35.680 --> 00:35:38.740 align:middle line:84%
when we come into our
activity, then we're more calm.

00:35:38.740 --> 00:35:42.110 align:middle line:84%
When things go more smoothly,
that we don't feel as upset.

00:35:42.110 --> 00:35:42.910 align:middle line:90%
